---
import BaseLayout from "@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import ContactFooter from "@/components/ContactFooter.astro";
import ArrowLink from "@/components/ArrowLink.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
	title="Jan Vitu — Marketing"
	description="Not louder. Remarkable. Marketing that earns trust, not just attention."
>
	<!-- Hero -->
	<section class="relative h-screen">
		<img
			src="/images/mist.avif"
			alt=""
			aria-hidden="true"
			class="absolute inset-0 h-full w-full object-contain object-top mix-blend-multiply pointer-events-none mask-[linear-gradient(to_top,transparent_0%,black_60%)] [-webkit-mask-image:linear-gradient(to_top,transparent_0%,black_60%)]"
		/>
		<div class="base-grid relative place-items-center h-full">
			<div
				class="col-start-2 col-end-12 md:col-start-4 md:col-end-10 text-center"
			>
				<h1 class="font-black uppercase tracking-tight leading-none">
					Marketing
				</h1>
				<p
					class="mt-4 max-w-[40ch] mx-auto text-xl text-neutral-600 md:text-2xl"
				>
					Not louder. Remarkable. Marketing that earns trust, not just attention.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- The contrast -->
	<section>
		<div class="base-grid py-24 md:py-32">
			<h2 class="col-start-2 col-end-12 md:col-start-3 md:col-end-9">
				Most marketing <span class="text-accent">interrupts</span>
			</h2>
			<p
				class="col-start-3 col-end-12 row-start-2 mt-4 text-xl text-neutral-700 sm:text-2xl md:col-start-4 md:col-end-9 md:mt-10 md:text-3xl"
			>
				The kind worth doing <b class="text-neutral-900">earns permission</b
				>.
			</p>
			<div
				class="col-start-3 col-end-12 row-start-3 mt-6 md:col-start-4 md:col-end-9 space-y-2 md:space-y-4"
			>
				<p class="text-sm text-neutral-700 sm:text-base md:text-xl">
					More ads, more channels, more noise. That is the default playbook.
					And it is exhausting - for the team and for the audience.
				</p>
				<p class="text-sm text-neutral-700 sm:text-base md:text-xl">
					There is a different way. Instead of fighting for attention, earn it.
					Instead of reaching everyone, matter to someone.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Principles — manifesto style -->
	<section>
		<div class="base-grid py-24 md:py-32">
			<h2 class="col-start-2 col-end-12 md:col-start-3 md:col-end-9">
				What I <span class="text-accent">believe</span>
			</h2>
		</div>

		<div class="base-grid">
			<div
				class="col-start-2 col-end-12 md:col-start-3 md:col-end-11 space-y-16 md:space-y-24"
			>
				<div class="max-w-[55ch]">
					<h3
						class="text-3xl font-black leading-tight md:text-4xl md:leading-tight"
					>
						Find the smallest audience worth serving.
					</h3>
					<p class="mt-4 text-neutral-600 md:text-lg">
						Not everyone needs to care. The right ten people who truly resonate
						with your story will do more than ten thousand who scroll past.
						Start small. Start specific. Earn the right to grow.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="max-w-[55ch] md:ml-auto">
					<h3
						class="text-3xl font-black leading-tight md:text-4xl md:leading-tight"
					>
						Be remarkable, not loud.
					</h3>
					<p class="mt-4 text-neutral-600 md:text-lg">
						Remarkable means worth remarking on. It is not about volume or
						frequency - it is about making something people feel compelled to
						share. If the work does not spread on its own, more spend will not
						fix it.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="max-w-[55ch]">
					<h3
						class="text-3xl font-black leading-tight md:text-4xl md:leading-tight"
					>
						Trust is built in small moments.
					</h3>
					<p class="mt-4 text-neutral-600 md:text-lg">
						Every touchpoint is a promise. The email, the landing page, the first
						interaction. Each one either builds trust or chips away at it. There
						are no neutral moments.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div class="max-w-[55ch] md:ml-auto">
					<h3
						class="text-3xl font-black leading-tight md:text-4xl md:leading-tight"
					>
						Stories move people. Tactics move metrics.
					</h3>
					<p class="mt-4 text-neutral-600 md:text-lg">
						You need both. But if you start with the tactic, you get a campaign.
						If you start with the story, you get a movement. The best marketing
						makes people feel like they belong to something.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- What I do -->
	<section>
		<div class="base-grid py-24 md:py-32">
			<h2 class="col-start-2 col-end-12 md:col-start-3 md:col-end-9">
				What I <span class="text-accent">do</span>
			</h2>
			<div
				class="col-start-3 col-end-12 row-start-2 mt-6 md:col-start-4 md:col-end-10 space-y-6 md:space-y-8"
			>
				<div>
					<h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-neutral-900 md:text-xl">
						Shape the narrative
					</h3>
					<p class="mt-1 text-neutral-600 md:text-lg">
						Find the core story that connects what you build to why people care.
						Not a tagline - a point of view that runs through everything.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-neutral-900 md:text-xl">
						Find the right audience
					</h3>
					<p class="mt-1 text-neutral-600 md:text-lg">
						Define who you are really for. Not demographics - the people who will
						care enough to tell others. Then build around them.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<h3 class="text-lg font-bold text-neutral-900 md:text-xl">
						Build permission, not just reach
					</h3>
					<p class="mt-1 text-neutral-600 md:text-lg">
						Channels and campaigns matter, but only when people want to hear from
						you. Earn attention first. Scale it second.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- Closing -->
	<section>
		<div class="base-grid py-24 md:py-32">
			<blockquote
				class="col-start-2 col-end-12 md:col-start-4 md:col-end-10 text-center"
			>
				<p
					class="text-2xl font-extralight italic leading-relaxed md:text-4xl md:leading-relaxed"
				>
					"People do not buy goods and services. They buy relations, stories,
					and magic."
				</p>
				<footer class="mt-6 text-neutral-500 md:text-lg">- Seth Godin</footer>
			</blockquote>
		</div>
	</section>

	<ContactFooter />
</BaseLayout>
